	<tr>
		<td width="10%" nowrap="nowrap">Post subject:&nbsp;</td>
		<td><b><span class="posthilit">N</span> <span class="posthilit">flag</span> after <span class="posthilit">CMP</span>/CPX/CPY instruction</b></td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
		<td colspan="2"><hr class="sep" />Has anyone any clue how it is used ?
<br />
<br />Honnestly I always use <span class="posthilit">CMP</span>/CPX/CPY instruction in pairs with the Z flags (to test equality) or with the C <span class="posthilit">flag</span>, to test &gt;= or &lt;
<br />
<br />Also V is affected and I'm pretty sure it's purpose is to compare signed numbers, although I don't remember ever using it.
<br />
<br />However, what about the <span class="posthilit">N</span> <span class="posthilit">flag</span> ? Supposedly it would be set as if a SBC instruction was used, exept the registers aren't affected.

		

		</td>
	</tr>
	</table>


	<hr width="85%" />

	<table width="85%" cellspacing="3" cellpadding="0" border="0" align="center">
	<tr>
		<td width="10%" nowrap="nowrap">Author:&nbsp;</td>
		<td><b>rainwarrior</b> [ Thu May 17, 2012 3:36 am ]</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
		<td width="10%" nowrap="nowrap">Post subject:&nbsp;</td>
		<td><b></b></td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
		<td colspan="2"><hr class="sep" /><a href="http://www.obelisk.demon.co.uk/6502/reference.html#CMP" class="postlink">http://www.obelisk.demon.co.uk/6502/reference.html#<span class="posthilit">CMP</span></a>
<br />
<br />Not exactly like if SBC was used, just a straight subtraction (carry is not involved), and then <span class="posthilit">N</span> is bit 7 of the result.
<br />
<br />I suppose it could be useful to know if a subtraction would result in bit 7 being set without having to clobber A to do it. It's not one of your normal comparison operations, but it might have some use. It's not appropriate for &gt; or &lt;, but if you ever want to know this:
<br />
<br />if (A-B modulo 256) &gt; 127
<br />
<br />I guess that's what it is.

		

		</td>
	</tr>
	</table>


	<hr width="85%" />

